 golden era of French film, usually viewed as a cinema preoccupied with masculinity. She shows how—in films such as Pépé le Moko, Le Crime de Monsieur Lange, and Zouzou—the realist chanteuse addresses female despair at the hopelessness of love. Conway also sheds light on the larger cultural implications of the shift from the intimate café-concert to the spectacular music hall, before the talkies displaced both kinds of live performance altogether.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMotion picture musiczFrancexHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictureszFrancexHistory. 0aPopular musiczFrancexHistory and criticism. 0aWomen singerszFrance. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  a1930s.  abeauty.  abelle epoque music hall.  acafe concert.  acinema lovers.  acinemaphiles.  acultural implications.  acultural roles.  acultural studies.  afemale desire.  afemininity.  afilm and culture.  afilm historians.  afrance.  afrench cinema.  afrench culture.  afrench film.  agender roles.  agolden era.  amusic hall careers.  amusic.  aparis.  apopular entertainment.  apopular music.  arealist performance.  arealist singer.  asingers.  atheatre.  awomen in film.  awomens roles.  aworking class life.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024407840uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093857140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938571423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938571/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY